Pima Indians Diabetes Dataset - Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Context:

This dataset is originally from the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases. The objective of the dataset is to diagnostically predict whether or not a patient has diabetes, based on certain diagnostic measurements included in the dataset.

In [1]:
from IPython.display import YouTubeVideo
YouTubeVideo("pN4HqWRybwk")
Out[1]:

Data Description:

The datasets consists of several medical predictor variables and one target variable `Outcome``.

Predictor variables includes the number of pregnancies the patient has had, their BMI, insulin level, age, and so on.

About the data

Numeric : Pregnancies : Number of times pregnant

Numeric : Glucose : Plasma glucose concentration at 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test

Numeric : BloodPressure : Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)

Numeric : SkinThickness : Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)

Numeric : Insulin : 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml)

Numeric : BMI : Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2)

Numeric : Pedigree : Diabetes pedigree function

Numeric : Age : Age (years)

Numeric : Outcome : Class variable (0 or 1)

Problem Statement:

Build a machine learning model to accurately predict whether or not the patients in the dataset have diabetes or not.

To begin, we will perform an exhaustive EDA, then draw conclusions from it. In an upcoming exercise, we will fit a model to the data and actually do the prediction.

  • there are 768 entries and 9 columns.

But there are values for some columns that do not make sense---they are marked as a zero (0) value.

For example, a zero value in BloodPressure variable does not make sense.

Also there are zero values in Glucose, SkinThickness, Insulin, and BMI variables.

These are actually missing values, a phenomenon that commonly occurs in experimental data gathering.

Step 2: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

a. MISSING VALUES

There are variables that have a minimum value of zero (0). For some variables, a value of zero does not make sense and thus indicates a missing value.

The following variables have an invalid zero value:

  1. BloodPressure
  2. Glucose
  3. SkinThickness
  4. Insulin
  5. BMI

Observation¶

Several variables have right-skewed, asymmetric distributions.

  • Age,
  • DiabetesPedigreeFunction,
  • Pregnancies),
  • SkinThickness,
  • Insulin.

This means that the Mean > Median.

c. DATA CLEANING

We now check:

  • the distributions for those variables that have an invalid zero value
  • the presence of "outliers"
  • the symmetry of the distributions (normal, left-skewed or right-skewed )

For this, we will use

  • boxplot
  • distplot (Histogram)

Once again, there are numerous outliers with large values.

Given the large number of NaN vlaues, it is higly recommended to replace them with a Median or a Mean.

  • Variables Glucose and BloodPressure do not have many outliers and we will fill them with their mean values
  • Variables SkinThickness, Insulin, and BMI have much disparity, we need to fill more data, so the median is recommended here.
In [36]:
pima_copy['Glucose'].fillna(pima_copy['Glucose'].mean(), inplace = True)
pima_copy['BloodPressure'].fillna(pima_copy['BloodPressure'].mean(), inplace = True)
pima_copy['SkinThickness'].fillna(pima_copy['SkinThickness'].median(), inplace = True)
pima_copy['Insulin'].fillna(pima_copy['Insulin'].median(), inplace = True)
pima_copy['BMI'].fillna(pima_copy['BMI'].median(), inplace = True)
# check:
print(pima_copy.isnull().sum())

We have replaced all NaN values with Mean or Median, and the data is now "clean"

In [49]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
sns.set(font_scale = 1.5)
sns.heatmap(corr, annot = True, cmap = 'plasma', vmin = -1, vmax = 1, linecolor='white', linewidths= 1)
plt.show()

From the above heatmap, we can conclude the following:

  1. There is no feature variable that has a strong correlation with the target Outcome as there is no value greater than +0.70, which would indicate a strong uphill (positive) linear relationship.

  2. The best predictor of the target variable Outcome is Glucose --> 0.49 which is near to 0.50 which indicates a moderate uphill (positive) relationship.

  3. The second best predictor of target variable Outcome is BMI --> 0.31 which indicates a weak uphill (positive) linear relationship.

  4. The correlation between BMI and SkinThickness is 0.54 which indicates that BMI increases with an increase in Skin Thickness.

  5. Correlation between Age and Pregnancies is 0.54 which indicates that an increase in age increases the chances of having a child.

  6. All the variables are somewhat correlated. So we cannot eliminate any variable just by looking at the correlation matrix.

  7. The effects of causality can be evaluated using partial correlations that attempt to eliminate confounding variables...
